The House of Representatives and the minister of Industry, Trade and Investment, Adeniyi Adebayo yesterday called for more stringent and effective verification exercise on all imported goods at various ports of entry across the country, in order to eradicate the menace of fake and counterfeited products. This was part of deliberations at an investigative hearing of an ad-hoc Committee of the House on Substandard and Counterfeited Products in Nigeria held at the National Assembly. The Committee chairman, Hon Femi Fakeye called on the agency to ensure more quality verification of all regulated products on arrival from various seaports and entry points into Nigeria. While declaring the hearing open, speaker of the House, Femi Gbajabiamila, lamented that substandard and counterfeited products in circulation in the Nigerian markets had wrecked many havocs. The speaker who was represented by the minority leader of the House, Hon. Ndudi Elumelu, said the public hearing was aimed at finding solutions to the challenge posed to the nation by the intrusion of fake and counterfeited products in the markets. He expressed worries that in 2019, there were so many fire outbreaks, 43 cases of collapse of buildings and other avoidable mishaps in many parts of the country due to fake and counterfeited products. Similarly, the minister in a brief oral presentation also lamented that there is currently pervasive circulation of fake, substandard and counterfeited products in the Nigerian markets. He informed the ad-hoc Committee that despite the appreciable efforts of the Standard Organisation of Nigeria (SON) to tackle the issue, there are cases of false declaration, outright forging of SON documents.